CommonFields.Title: Preparation and properties of poly(methylmethacrylate)–silica hybrid materials incorporating reactive silica nanoparticles
Author: Sugimoto, Hideki
Daimatsu, Kazuki
Nakanishi, Eiji
Ogasawara, Yutaka
Yasumura, Takashi
Inomata, Katsuhiro
CommonFields.Location: Graduate School of Engineering, Nagoya Institute of Technology, Gokiso-cho, Showa-ku, Nagoya 466-8555, Japan

Mixing.Description:
To introduce methacryloyl groups onto colloidal
            silica surfaces, a given amount of MOI and di-n-butyltin dilaurate
            (DBTL) (ca. 250–500 ppm) catalyst were added to EAc-ST, and the
            reaction was carried out at room temperature for 24 h with
            stirring.

Drying-Evaporation.Description:
To obtain a colloidal silica/MMA dispersion
          (MMA–silica), ethyl acetate was first removed from the mixed
          solution with a rotary evaporator.

Mixing.Description:
To prepare PMMA–silica hybrid copolymers, MMA was added
          to the MOI/colloidal silica dispersion described above. The
          copolymerization used benzoyl peroxide (BPO) as a free radical
          initiator, was carried out at 80°C for 24 h.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description:
The sample (thickness: 80 nm) was prepared for TEM with a
      microtome knife.

Fourier_Transform_Infrared_Spectroscopy.Description:
Used to characterize the reactive silica
      nanoparticles

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description:
TGA was carried out over the range 25–600°C with a platinum
      pan, at a heating rate of 10°C/min. Alumina powder was used as a
      reference material.

Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Equipment: Bruker model AVANCE 200 FT NMR spectrometer
Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Description:
Used to characterize the reactive silica
      nanoparticles
